15 Timezone Alignment:



SOLUTION:

Step 1: Identify the App Servers
The Nautilus Application Servers are typically App Server 1, 2, and 3 in Stratos Datacenter.

Step 2: Check Current Timezone on Each Server
First, let's check the current timezone configuration on each server:

For App Server 1:
bash
ssh username@stapp01
timedatectl
ls -la /etc/localtime
cat /etc/timezone
For App Server 2:
bash
ssh username@stapp02
timedatectl
For App Server 3:
bash
ssh username@stapp03
timedatectl
Step 3: Set Timezone to Asia/Manila on Each Server
Use timedatectl to set the timezone on each server:

For App Server 1:
bash
ssh username@stapp01
sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Manila
For App Server 2:
bash
ssh username@stapp02
sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Manila
For App Server 3:
bash
ssh username@stapp03
sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Manila
Step 4: Verify the Changes
Verify that the timezone has been successfully set to Asia/Manila on each server:

For App Server 1:
bash
ssh username@stapp01
timedatectl | grep "Time zone"
For App Server 2:
bash
ssh username@stapp02
timedatectl | grep "Time zone"
For App Server 3:
bash
ssh username@stapp03
timedatectl | grep "Time zone"
Complete Solution Script
Here's a complete script to configure all three app servers:

bash
#!/bin/bash

# Array of app servers
servers=("stapp01" "stapp02" "stapp03")

for server in "${servers[@]}"; do
    echo "=== Configuring timezone on $server ==="
    
    # Set timezone to Asia/Manila
    ssh username@$server "sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Manila"
    
    # Verify the change
    ssh username@$server "echo 'Timezone on $server:'; timedatectl | grep 'Time zone'"
    
    echo "=== $server completed ==="
    echo
done
Alternative Methods
If timedatectl is not available, use these alternative methods:

Method 2: Using symlink
bash
# Remove existing localtime symlink
sudo rm -f /etc/localtime

# Create new symlink to Asia/Manila timezone
sudo ln -sf /usr/share/zoneinfo/Asia/Manila /etc/localtime

# Update timezone file (on Debian/Ubuntu systems)
echo "Asia/Manila" | sudo tee /etc/timezone
Method 3: Using tzdata
bash
# On some systems, you can use tzdata
sudo dpkg-reconfigure tzdata
# Then select Asia -> Manila
One-Line Command for All Servers
You can use this one-liner to configure all servers at once:

bash
for server in stapp01 stapp02 stapp03; do
    echo "Setting Asia/Manila timezone on $server"
    ssh username@$server "sudo timedatectl set-timezone Asia/Manila && timedatectl | grep 'Time zone'"
done
Verification Commands
To thoroughly verify the timezone configuration:

bash
# Check current timezone and time
timedatectl

# Check the timezone file
ls -la /etc/localtime

# Check timezone content (on Debian/Ubuntu)
cat /etc/timezone

# Display current time with timezone
date
Expected Output
After successful configuration, you should see:

text
Time zone: Asia/Manila (PST, +0800)
When you run timedatectl | grep "Time zone" on each server.

Additional Time Synchronization (Optional)
To ensure time is also synchronized, you can check and configure NTP:

bash
# Check NTP status
timedatectl | grep "NTP enabled"

# Enable NTP if not enabled
sudo timedatectl set-ntp true

# Check time synchronization
timedatectl show-timesync -a
Complete Verification Script
Run this comprehensive verification on all servers:

bash
for server in stapp01 stapp02 stapp03; do
    echo "=== $server Timezone Verification ==="
    ssh username@$server "timedatectl | grep -E 'Time zone|Local time' && date && echo '---'"
    echo
done
Important Notes
No reboot required: Timezone changes take effect immediately

Existing processes: Some running processes may need to be restarted to pick up the new timezone

Sudo privileges: Required to change system timezone

Time synchronization: Consider enabling NTP to keep time accurate across all servers

The timezone has now been synchronized to Asia/Manila across all Nautilus Application Servers in the Stratos Datacenter. All servers should now display the correct local datacenter timezone.



